    {
      "text": "A 20-month-old child presents with a 36-hour history of fever, decreased oral intake, and has had one episode of vomiting. The child is alert but less interactive than usual. Vital signs are BP, 95/60 mm Hg; P, 140; R, 28; T, 38.4째C (101.1째F). Physical examination shows no focal findings, clear lungs, and normal skin without rash. The child received acetaminophen 2 hours ago. What is the most appropriate next step in management?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Perform chest x-ray and rapid streptococcal test"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Administer empiric antibiotics and observe"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Obtain cerebrospinal fluid analysis"
        },
        {
          "id": 4,
          "text": "Collect urine for urinalysis and culture"
        },
        {
          "id": 5,
          "text": "Obtain blood culture and complete blood count"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 4,
      "solution": "<div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>A) INCORRECT:</h4>This patient's presentation is not consistent with <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=mh0Vef&anker=Z36f83311c3582932defdae7a73e5730b\" data-learningcard-id=\"mh0Vef\" data-anker=\"Z36f83311c3582932defdae7a73e5730b\" data-sememe-id=\"rk0f6T\">pneumonia</a> or <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=wj0hcT&anker=Z19d5ecc633125a9c419ab01330d30ab3\" data-learningcard-id=\"wj0hcT\" data-anker=\"Z19d5ecc633125a9c419ab01330d30ab3\" data-section-id=\"8kYOp6\" data-sememe-id=\"ETb8sG\">pharyngitis</a>, making an alternative step in management more appropriate.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>B) INCORRECT:</h4>\n<a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=mm0VTg&anker=Z0d92af1eab239465721da02549c61854\" data-learningcard-id=\"mm0VTg\" data-anker=\"Z0d92af1eab239465721da02549c61854\" data-section-id=\"cubaJv\" data-sememe-id=\"yOadEk\">Empiric antibiotics</a> are reserved for children with <span data-sememe-id=\"3JcSFW0\">red flags</span> for serious bacterial infection or those who appear ill, but this child has no concerning features and requires diagnostic evaluation first to guide appropriate treatment.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>C) INCORRECT:</h4>\n<a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=-l0DzT&anker=Z4ab91b58e5629961fd4c7241b64712c7\" data-learningcard-id=\"-l0DzT\" data-anker=\"Z4ab91b58e5629961fd4c7241b64712c7\" data-section-id=\"vobAdu\" data-sememe-id=\"Tz06Hi\">Cerebrospinal fluid analysis</a> is indicated for patients with neurological symptoms, <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=ZR0Zlf&anker=Z0bc2adf708740e30072f4a749bf17295\" data-learningcard-id=\"ZR0Zlf\" data-anker=\"Z0bc2adf708740e30072f4a749bf17295\" data-section-id=\"gKaFfl\" data-sememe-id=\"esdxFr0\">signs of meningitis</a>, or other <span data-sememe-id=\"3JcSFW0\">red flags</span>. This child is alert and does not have <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=7704Mh&anker=Z5c6e37230ac0687b2722ec65d3bb632a\" data-learningcard-id=\"7704Mh\" data-anker=\"Z5c6e37230ac0687b2722ec65d3bb632a\" data-section-id=\"Zy1Zdj0\" data-sememe-id=\"R81lmi0\">altered mental status</a> or concerning neurological findings.</div><div><h4 style='color: #34d399; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>D) CORRECT:</h4>Correct -- In children aged 2 months to 3 years with <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=j50_Pg&anker=Za5de83449ff6a749e6c1348b93b1f3b1\" data-learningcard-id=\"j50_Pg\" data-anker=\"Za5de83449ff6a749e6c1348b93b1f3b1\" data-sememe-id=\"CL0q-g\">fever</a> of unknown source, <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=kg0mv2&anker=Zb8209254add9c4f1d8b458a49671b899\" data-learningcard-id=\"kg0mv2\" data-anker=\"Zb8209254add9c4f1d8b458a49671b899\" data-section-id=\"jJX_F_\" data-sememe-id=\"R6alkl\">urinalysis</a> with culture is the most appropriate next step because <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=7i04Gf&anker=Zc27d78347d45b1423debf25ad883dd4c\" data-learningcard-id=\"7i04Gf\" data-anker=\"Zc27d78347d45b1423debf25ad883dd4c\" data-sememe-id=\"4ib37t\">urinary tract infections</a> are the most common bacterial infection in this age group and often manifest with nonspecific symptoms such as <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=j50_Pg&anker=Za5de83449ff6a749e6c1348b93b1f3b1\" data-learningcard-id=\"j50_Pg\" data-anker=\"Za5de83449ff6a749e6c1348b93b1f3b1\" data-sememe-id=\"CL0q-g\">fever</a>, <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=7J04vS&anker=Z2f0b48ef2acaab783b03e4c8d2404f90\" data-learningcard-id=\"7J04vS\" data-anker=\"Z2f0b48ef2acaab783b03e4c8d2404f90\">vomiting</a>, and decreased oral intake.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>E) INCORRECT:</h4>\n<a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=7l04yT&anker=Zbbc1ac48182c8850d109967ff3d2e390\" data-learningcard-id=\"7l04yT\" data-anker=\"Zbbc1ac48182c8850d109967ff3d2e390\" data-sememe-id=\"kn0mtg\">Blood cultures</a> and <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=Ln0wFg&anker=Z4ccf935251884533761ac0c529e17a64\" data-learningcard-id=\"Ln0wFg\" data-anker=\"Z4ccf935251884533761ac0c529e17a64\" data-section-id=\"OU1IWT0\" data-sememe-id=\"-lbDzF\">complete blood count</a> are indicated for patients with <span data-sememe-id=\"3JcSFW0\">red flags</span> for serious bacterial infection, but this child has no <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=xm0E3g&anker=Zfc5000635c82df81690cce04f017a9cc\" data-learningcard-id=\"xm0E3g\" data-anker=\"Zfc5000635c82df81690cce04f017a9cc\" data-section-id=\"qDbC2D\" data-sememe-id=\"du1oJi0\">signs of sepsis</a> or other concerning features that would warrant invasive blood testing at this time.</div>",
